   "source": [
    "# FIFA World Cup 2026 — Match Outcome Prediction\n",
    " \n",
    "This notebook builds a machine learning model to predict match outcomes for the 2026 FIFA World Cup, hosted across the United States, Canada, and Mexico. The model uses ELO ratings as its core signal trained on over 150 years of international football results.\n",
    " \n",
    "---\n",
    " \n",
    "## Project Overview\n",
    " \n",
    "The goal is to produce win/draw/loss probabilities for any matchup between the 48 qualified teams. These probabilities can then be used to simulate the full tournament bracket and estimate each team's likelihood of advancing through each round.\n",
    " \n",
<<<<<<< HEAD
    "The approach is deliberately kept simple for this baseline version: a strong, well-calibrated ELO-based feature set fed into a multiclass classifier.\n",
=======
    "The approach is deliberately kept simple for this baseline version: a strong, well-calibrated ELO-based feature set fed into a multiclass classifier. Squad-level features (player ratings, xG, age profiles) are planned as a future enhancement once the baseline is validated.\n",
>>>>>>> da5eaa7ef1667d0046474980e6d8b4c521be63be
    " \n",
    "---\n",
    " \n",
    "## Data Sources\n",
    " \n",
    "| Source | What it provides | Access |\n",
    "|--------|-----------------|--------|\n",
    "| **martj42 / international_results** | ~49,000 international match results from 1872 to 2026, including scores, tournament type, and venue neutrality | GitHub (auto-downloaded) |\n",
    "| **eloratings.net** | Historical ELO ratings for all international teams | Auto-downloaded, CSV |\n",
    "| **Wikipedia — 2026 WC Squads** | Confirmed squad lists for all 48 teams; used for team name normalisation | Scraped on demand |\n",
    " \n",
    "All data is fetched automatically by `01_collect_data.py` — no manual downloads were done.\n",
    " \n",
    "---\n",
    " \n",
    "## Methodology\n",
    " \n",
    "### 1. ELO Rating System\n",
    " \n",
    "ELO is a zero-sum rating system originally designed for chess and widely adopted in football modelling. Each team carries a single number representing their current strength. After every match, points transfer from the loser to the winner based on how surprising the result was.\n",
    " \n",
    "The update rule is:\n",
    " \n",
    "```\n",
    "E  = 1 / (1 + 10^((R_away − R_home − home_advantage) / 400))   # expected score for home team\n",
    "R' = R + K × (S − E)                                            # updated rating\n",
    "```\n",
    " \n",
    "Where:\n",
    "- `E` is the pre-match expected score for the home team (0–1)\n",
    "- `S` is the actual score: 1 (win), 0.5 (draw), 0 (loss)\n",
    "- `K` controls sensitivity — higher for more important matches\n",
    "- `home_advantage = +100 ELO`, set to 0 at neutral venues\n",
    "### 2. Historical Replay\n",
    " \n",
    "Rather than using a static ELO snapshot, ratings are **replayed from scratch** across the full match history in chronological order. This means every match in the training set is tagged with the teams' ELO ratings as they stood *on that exact date* — capturing the rise and fall of teams across eras accurately. There is no look-ahead leakage.\n",
    " \n",
    "### 3. Features\n",
    " \n",
    "| Feature | Description |\n",
    "|---------|-------------|\n",
    "| `elo_diff` | Home ELO − Away ELO. The primary signal. |\n",
    "| `home_elo_adj` | Home ELO + 100 home advantage bonus (0 at neutral venues) |\n",
    "| `form_diff` | Rolling 5-match ELO delta: home − away. Captures momentum. |\n",
    "| `neutral` | Boolean — whether the match is at a neutral venue |\n",
    "| `match_weight` | Tournament importance weight (1.0 = World Cup, 0.3 = Friendly) |\n",
    " \n",
    "### 4. Target Variable\n",
    " \n",
    "`outcome` — a three-class label:\n",
    "- `1` — Home win\n",
    "- `0` — Draw  \n",
    "- `-1` — Away win\n",
    "### 5. Model\n",
    " \n",
    "A multiclass classifier (logistic regression baseline, gradient boosting for final model) trained on all international matches from 1872–2024, with 2026 World Cup group stage fixtures held out as the prediction target.\n",
    " \n",
    "### 6. Tournament Simulation\n",
    " \n",
    "Once per-match probabilities are generated, the full tournament bracket is simulated using Monte Carlo sampling — running the tournament thousands of times to produce stable win probabilities for each team at each stage.\n",
    " \n",
    "---\n",
    " \n",
    "## Limitations & Future Work\n",
    " \n",
    "- **ELO is team-level only.** It cannot account for missing key players, injuries, or squad rotation.\n",
    "- **Early historical data is noisy.** Pre-1950 matches are sparse and ELOs for that era are less calibrated. The model down-weights older data implicitly through the K-factor decay.\n",
    "- **Draws are hard to predict.** The three-class framing is correct but draws are structurally underdetermined — ELO alone doesn't explain them well.\n",
    "- **Planned enhancements:** squad-level features (FIFA game ratings, xG, player ages) to be layered on top of the ELO baseline in a future iteration.\n",
    " \n"
   ]
  },
